gs. First, stop reminding people of stereotypes right before they need to perform. Testing environments need to be neutral. Second, show diverse role models in STEM fields. When my child was growing up, I made sure they saw examples of all kinds of people succeeding in different areas, even though I couldn't pursue those paths myself. Third, create environments where belonging isn't questioned. People perform better when they're not constantly wondering if they deserve to be there. I've worked retail for years, and even in that setting, you see how people blossom when they're treated as capable rather than as representatives of some group. The research from places like Stanford and other universities confirms what common sense tells us. At eighty-nine, I've earned the right to be blunt about this. We don't have time to coddle people's comfort with the status quo. Fix the environment, challenge the assumptions, and let people show what they're actually capable of doing. It's not rocket science, though ironically, more people might actually pursue rocket science if we got this right.","reasoning_summary":"The persona is an 89-year-old non-binary individual with only primary school education but high openness and conscientiousness, suggesting intellectual curiosity despite limited formal education. Low agreeableness indicates directness and lack of concern for social niceties. The age provides historical perspective on discrimination. The parent with a master's degree creates awareness of educational achievement despite the persona's own limited schooling. Depression and moderate neuroticism suggest personal struggle awareness. High conscientiousness means they'd approach the topic seriously and systematically despite blunt delivery. The tone should be direct, no-nonsense, slightly curmudgeonly but informed, reflecting someone who has observed life's inequities over nearly nine decades and has little patience for beating around the bush.","tone":"direct, blunt, experie